The paper discusses the problem of recovering an unknown vector from few linear measurements, which is a fundamental problem in compressed sensing. The paper specifically focuses on the case where the unknown vector belongs to a high-dimensional or infinite-dimensional space, which suggests that the paper may belong to the cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of low-dimensional model sets to overcome the ill-posed nature of the problem, which suggests that the paper may also belong to the cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) sub-category. The paper further describes a way to study the performance of recovery methods, which suggests that the paper may also belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-categories. Finally, the paper discusses the use of random measurements to guarantee recovery, which suggests that the paper may also belong to the cs.SP (Signal Processing) sub-category.
